To integrate your own JavaScript code directly into Web Debugging (Web-Debug), you'll need to use a combination of tools that allow for dynamic and interactive visualization of logs. Here’s how you can achieve this:

1. **Prometheus**: Prometheus is a powerful tool designed for monitoring and data collection across various systems. It can be used to visualize your logs directly.

2. **Tableau or other dashboards**: To display the data in a more interactive way, you might use tools like Tableau that allow real-time updates of data from external sources like Web-Debug.

### Steps to Integrate Your JavaScript Code with Web Debugging:

1. **Install Prometheus**: Install Prometheus on your server.

2. **Set up a monitoring system**:
   - Use the built-in features of Prometheus, such as custom metrics and alerts.
   - For real-time updates, you can use tools like Grafana or Tableau.

3. **Configure Web Debugging to use Prometheus**:
   - Install Web Debugging (Web-Debug) on your server.
   - Set up a webhook to monitor your logs from Prometheus.
   - Use the built-in dashboarding capabilities of Web Debugging to display data in real-time.

### Example Workflow:

1. **Set Up Your Logging System**:
   - Configure your logging system to send logs to Web Debugging (Web-Debug) and Prometheus.

2. **Configure Web Debugging to Use Prometheus**:
   - Install and configure Web Debugging.
   - Set up a webhook that captures data from Prometheus and sends it to Web Debugging in real-time.

3. **Real-Time Monitoring**:
   - When you send logs to Web Debug, it will automatically update its dashboard with the latest logs.

### Example Code Snippet:

```javascript
// Example JavaScript code snippet for logging events
var user = {
  name: "John Doe",
  email: "john.doe@example.com"
};

user.name = "Jane Doe"; // Update user data in the log

WebDebug.init({
  source: 'someSourceName',
  title: 'User Activity'
}, function(data) {
  console.log('Data received:', data);
});
```

### HTML and CSS:

You can use a simple HTML and CSS layout to display the logs directly from Web Debug:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Web Debug Example</title>
<style>
  body {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  }
  .container {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 600px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    background-color: #f8f9fa;
    margin: auto;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="container">
  <h1>Web Debug Example</h1>
  <div id="logs"></div>
</div>

<script>
  WebDebug.init({
    source: 'yourSourceName',
    title: 'User Activity'
  });

  function updateLogs() {
    var data = WebDebug.get('user_activity', { start: new Date(), end: new Date() });
    document.getElementById('logs').innerHTML = JSON.stringify(data, null, 2);
  }

  setInterval(updateLogs, 1000);
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

- **HTML Structure**: A simple HTML structure with a container for displaying the logs.
- **CSS Styling**: Basic styling to make the layout responsive and visually appealing.

### Running Web Debug (Web-Debug):

1. Start your Web Debug server using `webdebug start`.
2. Set up your logging system by configuring it in Web Debug.
3. Configure Prometheus to send data to Web Debug.
4. Use Web Debug’s built-in dashboarding capabilities to display the logs and filter based on specific criteria.

This setup allows you to easily visualize real-time user activity directly from Web Debug, leveraging the power of both tools for a more dynamic and interactive logging experience.
